                    Tacky Races, or Less can be More!

 The other day, I was looking at two very similar actions that seemed to 
drag  on  for an age on two different computers.  Opening  a  directory 
where there were a large bunch of files took a while on a 16 mhz Falcon 
fitted  with  Jinnee desktop,  and it also seemed to drag for  a  whale 
holding its breath styled pause, on my 200 mhz Pentium work beast.

You might be surprised that I, a dedicated PC wintel PC loather, spends 
the  greater  part of the working day on one.  Necessary evil,  they're 
sort  of  very common in business,  but at least I get some  first-hand 
knowledge of the 'enemy' and its funny little ways!

Okay, fit the following...

200  mhz Pentium 2 PC,  bog-standard graphics card,  no fancy hardware, 
Windows 95. To open a new directory containing 44 files, 7 seconds.

16 mhz 68030 Falcon, no graphics card, MagiC O/S and Jinnee Desktop. To 
open a new directory containing 196 files, 6-7 seconds!

To throw a further interesting light onto this,  with a 50 mhz Centurbo 
2, the response with Jinnee/MagiC is reduced to 1-2 seconds. An upgrade 
to 600 mhz would give the PC comparable performance!

People  who  say that a good graphics card would help the  PC's  cause, 
are I think, missing the point somewhat!


