                          Fantasy ZX Spectrum?

 It seems to merely  emulate  a famous old computer isn't enough for  some 
people?  Here's  an interesting report from a Speccy equivalent to  our 
own Atari DHS 'Scene News' Take it away boys!                          
                 
                      ŒNEW  SPECTRUM EMULATOR 

There  is   ANOTHER   new  Spectrum   emulator released,  but  with   a  
difference  -  this one gives the Spectrum  256  colours!  And no, it's 
not a phasing / paging trick like has been seen on the 128's.

The  emulator,  written  by  Inigo  Ayo  and David  Goti  emulates  not  
one   but   TWO  processors  -  the standard   Z80   processor,  and  a 
ficticious processor called Z80_GFX.

This  processor uses it's own memory region in which each  position  is  
64  bits  wide.  This allows the new processor to move data and operate 
with  them  so  it  can  display the  results  in  256   colours.   The  
only drawback is that  before  a  game  can  be played in 256  colours, 
it must  have  it's colour  palette  edited  beforehand.   But,  eleven 
games  have been  converted  so  far (mostly Dinamic and Hewson  and  a 
couple of Ultimate titles) and  the  results  really are amazing!

Besides  this  remarkable  function,   the program emulates a  standard 
48k   Spectrum, offers  joystick  control  and  48k  sound through  the 
PC  speaker.  There  is  also  a very  thorough  debugger  and  Z80   /  
SNA snapshot format support.

 So  there  you have it ,   proof that anything is possible if you  really 
want it to happen! Also, how soon before we start getting emulated ST's 
with 'fantasy' extra features not put on the original? I'm sure there's 
some emulator coder out there thinking, "If only....?"
 
 
                            Zilog a Go-Go!
 
Also cribbed from the same news-pages which gave us the story above, an 
interesting  piece about a chip manufacturer who once held most of  the 
8-bit personal computer market in its hands, before Intel waded in.

Hardware designers,  bored with the present bland Intel consensus (with 
a  fleeting promise of new PPC and RISC designs?) Well why not  take  a 
look at this!
 
Zilog   have  manufactured  a   completely   new processor.   The  eZ80  
executes     code   four     times   faster   than   the    traditional 
processor and can even operate upto 80Mhz,   while that may not be fast 
for  a  PC,   that is some TWENTY TWO times faster  than   the original 
Spectrum! 

The processor can  also address 16 Megabytes, as  opposed  to  the 64Kb  
of   the   Z80A.   The  new  chip  also carries a  new   multiplication  
engine  and TCP/IP  stack  (a  requirement   for   the internet).  

Zilog   have   only  released  a small amount of data on the  chip   at  
this time  (25th  September)  which  is  later   in  this  issue,  it's 
unknown  whether  the   chip could  be  used  in  a  Spectrum   without  
heavy modification to the PCB.
 

